<span class="displaytext">jefferson city, mo. -- former arkansas governor and presidential candidate (candidate full) announced the endorsement of 31 missouri legislators during a news conference tuesday in jefferson city, mo. (candidate last) spoke to a standing-room-only crowd of about 250 people in a conference room of the associated industries of missouri building. <p>since he is from neighboring arkansas, (candidate last) said he has certain kinship with missouri.</p><p>"i want to turn the nonsense of our tax system to the common sense of what's often called the fairtax," (candidate last) said. he also discussed being pro-life was well as his stance on homeland security, terrorism and the economy.</p><p>state senator delbert scott and state rep. scott lipke, two co-chairs of (candidate last)'s missouri campaign, introduced (candidate last) and then presented the other state legislators supporting him. </p><p>"he is a solid conservative who isn't afraid to tell it like it is," lipke said . "as governor, (candidate last) cut taxes where he could and made good use of the revenues he had improving roads and education in arkansas. that is the kind of common sense leadership the country needs right now." </p><p>besides scott and lipken, the other co-chairs of the (candidate last) campaign are rep. brian yates and rep. mike sutherland.</p><p>other missouri legislators endorsing (candidate last) include:</p><p>missouri faith and family chair, senator john loudon<br/>representative jim avery<br/>representative brian baker<br/>senator matt bartle<br/>representative mark bruns<br/>representative wayne cooper<br/>representative cynthia davis<br/>representative ed emery<br/>representative barney fisher<br/>representative ward franz<br/>representative steve hunter<br/>representative will kraus<br/>senator brad lager<br/>representative bob may<br/>senator rob mayer<br/>representative brian munzlinger<br/>representative bob nance<br/>representative brian nieves<br/>representat